echanics\nDate: 2026-03-01\nURL: https://www.ainvest.com/news/kalshi-21-7m-liqui
dity-event-test-prediction-market-flow-mechanics-2603/\nSummary: The trading eve
nt was massive, with $21.7 million in volume across two markets on Saturday befo
re the halt. The largest contracts, for March 1 and April 1, accounted for 91% o
f total open interest, concentrating the flow into a few key positions. This cre
ated a defined liquidity event as the market froze.\n\nCEO Tarek Mansour announc
ed the settlement policy: positions would be settled based on the last price tra
ded before the first strike, with all fees fully refunded on trades opened after
that moment. The platform would not allow users to profit directly from a death,
a policy Mansour framed as consistent with existing rules.\n\nThe mechanics were
straightforward. Trading halted around 3 PM ET, freezing the market. The platfor
m then processed reimbursements for affected trades, with a site-wide banner con
firming credits had been reflected in user balances. This created a clear, albei
t rushed, settlement path.\n\n Market Mechanics and Competitive Flow\n\nThe liqu
idity event starkly contrasts the two platforms\' scale. Kalshi\'s $21\n\nThe tr
ading event was massive, with $21.7 million in volume across two markets on Satu
rday before the halt. The largest contracts, for March 1 and April 1, accounted 
for 91% of total open interest, concentrating the flow into a few key positions.
This created a defined liquidity event as the market froze.\n\nCEO Tarek Mansour
announced the settlement policy: positions would be settled based on the last pr
ice traded before the first strike, with all fees fully refunded on trades opene
d after that moment. The platform would not allow users to profit directly from 
a death, a policy Mansour framed as consistent with existing rules.\n\nThe mecha
nics were straightforward. Trading halted around 3 PM ET, freezing the market. T
he platform then processed reimbursements for affected trades, with a site-wide 
banner confirming credits had been reflected in user balances. This created a cl
ear, albeit rushed, settlement path.\n\n## Market Mechanics and Competitive Flow
\n\nThe liquidity event starkly contrasts the two platforms\' scale. Kalshi\'s $
21.7 million in volume across its two markets was dwarfed by Polymarket\'s more 
than $529 million in volume on a similar \'US strikes Iran\' contract since Dece
mber. This divergence highlights a fundamental flow difference: Polymarket\'s op
en, global structure attracted massive speculative capital, while Kalshi\'s regu
lated, death-carveout model created a more constrained, event-driven liquidity p
ool.\n\nKalshi\'s settlement policy was a direct application of its existing rul
es, not a new rule. CEO Tarek Mansour framed it as consistent with the platform\
's existing \'death carveout\', which prevents payouts triggered by a subject\'s
death. The mechanism-settling at the last price traded before the first strike a
nd refunding fees-was designed to stop users from profiting directly from a deat
h while keeping the market\'s price action intact. This policy, however, left th
e market\'s structural ambiguity exposed.\n\nThe event\'s liquidity was also att
racted by real-time news. Prices on Kalshi\'s Khamenei contracts began climbing 
shortly after Trump\'s Truth Social post on Saturday morning, showing how quickl
y the platform\'s flow can be drawn by high-impact geopolitical signals. Yet the
subsequent halt and settlement created a closed loop, freezing the market and it
s price discovery at a specific, volatile moment.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Kalshi Launch
