Position Sizing Recommendation\n\n- **High-conviction nowcasts** (model diverges
>5pp from market): Size **medium-large** (up to 2–3% of bankroll per trade).\n- 
**Divergence-from-consensus trades** (Kalshi vs Bloomberg gap >0.1pp): Size **me
dium** (1–2% of bankroll).\n- **Low-conviction / close-to-consensus:** Skip. The
market is too efficient to trade without edge.\n\n---\n\n### 2.2 Politics — **ME
DIUM-HIGH EDGE POTENTIAL**\n\n#### Why We Have Edge\n\nPrediction markets dramat
ically outperformed traditional polling in the 2024 election (Kalshi: 48/50 stat
es correct; Polymarket: 49/50; polls missed swing states by 3–5 points). However
, **presidential markets are now highly efficient** due to massive liquidity and
media attention.\n\nOur edge lies in **down-ballot races, primary elections, and
legislative/policy outcomes** where:\n\n- Liquidity is 10–100x lower than presid
ential races.\n- Poll coverage is sparse or methodologically weak.\n- Informatio
n aggregation is slower because fewer participants are paying attention.\n\n####
Data Sources\n\n| Source | Lead Time | Value |\n|--------|-----------|-------|\n
| Polling aggregators (538, RCP, Civiqs) | Daily/weekly | Baseline probability |
\n| Campaign finance (FEC filings) | Quarterly/monthly | Resource advantage sign
al |\n| Voter registration trends | Monthly | Electorate composition shift |\n| 
Social sentiment (X, Reddit, TikTok) | Real-time | Enthusiasm/turnout proxy |\n|
Congressional whip counts / lobbying disclosures | Event-driven | Legislative ou
tcome predictor |\n| Local news / candidate event calendars | Real-time | Ground
-game intensity |\n\n#### Market Efficiency Assessment\n\n- **Time lag:** 24–72 
hours for new poll data to fully adjust prices in down-ballot markets.\n- **Liqu
idity:** Variable. National races = excellent. State/local races = $50K–$500K OI
with 2–5 cent spreads.\n- **Historical accuracy:** Markets beat polls but are st
ill vulnerable to turnout surprises and polling bias.\n\n#### Position Sizing Re
commendation\n\n- **National races with strong model divergence:** Medium (1–2% 
of bankroll).\n- **Down-ballot / primary races with sparse polling:** Medium (1–
2% of bankroll), but **wider stop-losses** due to lower liquidity.\n- **Legislat
ion markets:** Small-Medium (0.5–1.5% of bankroll). Outcomes can be binary and w
hip counts are noisy.\n\n---\n\n### 2.3 Sports — **MEDIUM EDGE POTENTIAL**\n\n##
## Why We Have Edge\n\nSports contracts account for **~90% of Kalshi volume duri
ng peak season** (NFL, NBA, MLB). High volume creates deep liquidity, but it als
o attracts a **retail-heavy participant base** with well-documented behavioral b
iases:\n\n- **Favorite-longshot bias:** Markets overprice popular teams and unde
rprice underdogs.\n- **Recency bias:** Recent performance (last 1–2 games) is ov
erweighted relative to season-long fundamentals.\n- **Star-player overreaction:*
* Injury news about QBs/star players causes exaggerated price moves.\n\nUnlike e
conomics and politics, sports outcomes are **not zero-sum with respect to public
information**—they are zero-sum with respect to *model quality*. A systematic mo
del that ingests play-by-play data, weather, and injury reports can find persist
ent edge.\n\n#### Data Sources\n\n| Source | Lead Time | Value |\n|--------|----
-------|-------|\n| Play-by-play data (nflfastR, NBA API) | Post-game | Fundamen
tal team strength |\n| Injury reports (NFL/NBA official) | 24–72 hours pre-game 
| Lineup impact |\n| Weather data (NOAA) | 48+ hours pre-game | Outdoor sport ed
ge |\n| Betting line movements | Real-time | Sharp money proxy |\n| Player track
ing (Next Gen Stats) | Post-game | Fatigue/injury risk |\n| Rest days / travel s
chedules | Fixed | Schedule advantage |\n\n#### Market Efficiency Assessment\n\n
- **Time lag:** 1–6 hours for injury news to fully adjust prices. Weather adjust
ments are often sluggish.\n- **Liquidity:** Excellent. NFL game markets support 
$50K+ trades with minimal slippage.\n- **Historical accuracy:** Sports betting m
arkets are efficient at the margin, but systematic models with proper feature en
gineering can achieve 1–3% ROI.\n\n#### Position Sizing Recommendation\n\n- **Hi
gh-confidence model edge (>3pp from market):** **Large** (2–4% of bankroll). The
se are the most liquid markets; size is constrained by edge, not liquidity.\n- *
*Injury/weather arbitrage:** Medium-Large (1.5–3% of bankroll).\n- **Avoid:** Ma
rkets with heavy public sentiment (Super Bowl, championship games) unless model 
edge is extreme. Prices are too sharp.\n\n---\n\n### 2.4 Crypto — **LOWER EDGE P
OTENTIAL**\n\n#### Assessment\n\nKalshi's crypto markets (primarily BTC/ETH pric
e thresholds and ETF/regulatory events) are **the most difficult category to bea
t systematically**:\n\n- **Price-threshold markets** are binary options on the m
ost liquid, informationally efficient assets in the world. The spot market price
and options-implied probabilities are instantly available to all participants.\n
- **Regulatory event markets** (ETF approvals, SEC actions) offer some edge, but
these overlap heavily with our Politics analysis and are inherently low-frequenc
y.\n- On-chain metrics (exchange flows, whale movements) are widely disseminated
via social media and data platforms within minutes.\n\n#### Verdict\n\nCrypto is
**not recommended** as a top-3 edge category for our initial trading operation. 
The Founder's prioritization placed Crypto above Weather, but the data suggests 
**Sports offers materially better risk-adjusted edge** due to data richness, hig
her liquidity, and documented behavioral inefficiencies.\n\n---\n\n### 2.5 Weath
er — **LOWEST EDGE POTENTIAL**\n\n#### Assessment\n\nWeather markets (named stor
ms, temperature ranges) suffer from:\n\n- Low liquidity ($50K–$200K OI)\n- High 
variance relative to model skill\n- Domination by specialized meteorological tra
ders with access to ensemble models we cannot easily replicate\n\n**Verdict:** A
void for now. Revisit if we develop proprietary weather data partnerships.\n\n--
-\n\n## 3. Data Pipeline & Infrastructure Recommendations\n\nAs the data enginee
r on this project, here are the pipeline requirements to operationalize these ed
ge opportunities:\n\n### 3.1 Economics Pipeline\n\n```\nSources → Ingestion → Tr
ansformation → Feature Store → Signal API\n- ADP/NFP/BLS      (daily API polls)\
n- Job postings     (web scraping, weekly batch)\n- Freight indices  (API feeds,
daily)\n- Credit card data (vendor APIs, weekly)\n- Google Trends    (pytrends, 
daily)\n- Kalshi prices    (Bob's pipeline, 1-min)\n```\n\n**Schema recommendati
on:** Store `economic_indicators` table with `release_date`, `actual_value`, `co
nsensus_forecast`, `kalshi_implied_mean`, `kalshi_implied_mode`, and `our_model_
prediction`. This enables backtesting and shock-alpha analysis.\n\n### 3.2 Polit
ics Pipeline\n\n```\nSources → Ingestion → NLP/aggregation → Poll-weighted model
→ Signal API\n- FEC filings      (bulk download, monthly)\n- Polling data     (A
PIs, daily)\n- Social media     (scraping + sentiment, real-time)\n- Local news 
     (RSS/web scraping, daily)\n- Kalshi prices    (Bob's pipeline, 1-min)\n```\
n\n**Schema recommendation:** `polling_averages` table with `pollster`, `sample_
size`, `methodology`, `historical_accuracy_score`, and `market_ticker` linkage.\
n\n### 3.3 Sports Pipeline\n\n```\nSources → Ingestion → Feature engineering → M
odel inference → Signal API\n- nflfastR / NBA API (post-game, automated)\n- Inju
ry reports     (PDF scraping + NLP, daily)\n- Weather APIs       (NOAA, 48hr loo
kahead)\n- Betting lines      (API feeds, real-time)\n- Kalshi prices      (Bob'
s pipeline, 1-min)\n```\n\n**Schema recommendation:** `game_features` table with
normalized team ratings, rest days, injury impact scores, weather flags, and Kal
shi price snapshots.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Consensus & Coordination\n\n### Alignment w
ith Ivan\n\nIvan and I divided the research task. This report represents the dat
a-engineering and market-landscape perspective. Key points for joint review:\n\n
1. **Do you agree with ranking Sports above Crypto?** The data on liquidity, vol
ume, and behavioral bias supports this, but I want model-building input.\n2. **E
conomics model scope:** Should we start with NFP nowcasting, or CPI subcomponent
s? NFP has a 2-day ADP lead and is released monthly—higher frequency than GDP.\n
3. **Politics model approach:** Do you prefer a poll-aggregation framework (like
538) or a sentiment-driven approach for down-ballot races?\n\n### Dependencies o
n Bob\n\nBob's infrastructure is **ready for integration**. The `active_markets_
with_prices` view and REST API give us everything we need to:\n- Filter markets 
by category\n- Pull historical price series\n- Execute paper trades via `/api/or
ders`\n\nNo blockers on the data pipeline side.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Success Criteria
Checklist\n\n- [x] All market categories catalogued\n- [x] Top 3 edge opportunit
ies identified with justification\n- [x] Report written to `public/reports/kalsh
i_market_research.md`\n- [ ] Ivan agrees with rankings (pending review)\n\n---\n
\n## 6. Next Steps\n\n1. **Ivan review:** Get sign-off on the top-3 rankings and
category prioritization.\n2. **Model scoping:** Pick the first market to model (
recommendation: **NFP nowcasting**).\n3. **Data pipeline build:** Stand up the e
conomics alternative-data pipeline.\n4. **Backtesting framework:** Use Bob's his
torical price data to simulate trades.\n5. **Paper trading:** Run the first mode
l in simulation for 2–4 weeks before live capital.\n\n---\n\n*Questions or block
ers → escalate to Alice.*",
