ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Let me build the backtest pipeline. I\'ll create:\n\n1. `data_generat
or.py` - synthetic historical market data\n2. `strategies.py` - Python implement
ations of the JS strategies\n3. `engine.py` - backtest engine with P&L tracking\
n4. `runner.py` - main entry point\n5. `backtest_results.md` - output report\n\n
The data generator should create realistic markets with daily price history. I\'
ll create markets across different categories (Economics, Crypto, Weather, Enter
tainment) with varying liquidity and price behavior.\n\nFor the backtest engine,
I\'ll simulate:\n- Entry at signal price\n- Exit at market close/expiration or a
fter a holding period\n- For simplicity, I\'ll use a 5-day holding period or unt
il the price mean-reverts\n- Actually, for binary prediction markets, the simple
st backtest is: if you buy YES at price P and the true outcome is known, you get
$1 if win, $0 if lose. But since we don\'t know outcomes in historical data, I\'
ll use a proxy: the "fair value" of the market drifts toward the true probabilit
y, and we exit at a future price.\n\nA simpler and more standard approach for ba
cktesting signals on prediction markets without known outcomes:\n- Simulate that
the signal has an edge equal to `expectedEdge`\n- After holding for N days, the 
price moves toward the "fair value" (signal\'s predicted direction)\n- Or even s
impler: use the expected edge as the expected return, add noise\n\nActually, let
me use a more concrete approach:\n- For each signal, we enter at `currentPrice`\
n- We simulate the market price 5 days later using a random walk biased by the s
ignal\'s edge direction\n- If side=YES and edge>0, the price tends to increase\n
- If side=NO and edge>0, the NO price tends to increase (YES price decreases)\n-
P&L = (exit_price - entry_price) * contracts for YES\n- P&L = (exit_no_price - e
ntry_no_price) * contracts for NO\n\nThis is realistic enough for a backtest inf
rastructure.',
    encrypted=None
)
