n- We hold for a fixed period (e.g., 5 days) or until the market "resolves"\n- S
ince we don\'t have actual outcomes, I\'ll simulate exit prices with a bias towa
rd the signal direction\n- A simple model: exit_price = entry_price + direction 
* edge * random_factor\n- Where direction = +1 for YES long, -1 for YES short (N
O long)\n- This captures the idea that signals with higher edge tend to be more 
profitable\n\nActually, for a more realistic backtest on synthetic data, I can u
se the actual future prices from the generated history. Since the data is a rand
om walk, there\'s no real edge, but we can at least measure how the strategies w
ould have performed on this specific random walk. The backtest is about the *inf
rastructure*, not proving profitability.\n\nSo the approach:\n- Entry at signal 
price on day T\n- Exit at day T+H (e.g., T+5) actual price from the historical d
ata\n- P&L = (exit_price - entry_price) * contracts for YES side\n- P&L = (exit_
no_price - entry_no_price) * contracts for NO side\n\nThis is honest and shows t
he backtest infrastructure works.',
